WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.280
My name is Joseph Richey, and when I'm not working at my day job as a data analyst, I'm a volunteer firefighter.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:11.760
It's June 20th, 2024, at 8 11 p.m.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:20.120
I'm sitting with my lovely wife eating dinner, when all of a sudden my pager goes off. Yes, it's 2024 and we still use pagers.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:26.120
I am quickly up and glance at my phone to see what we're headed to. Structure fire.

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:31.639
I'm out the door moments later, running to the fire station that's about half a block from my house.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:35.959
I get there, start throwing my gear as others stream in and do the same.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:40.680
Four and a half minutes after we're paged, we're headed out the door,

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.720
a fire engine full of firefighters, heading to our neighboring town to fight a house fire.

00:00:46.759 --> 00:00:52.599
On the way, my heart is pounding. I try and focus, listening to the radio to find out what we're

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:58.520
headed to. Where is the fire? How bad is it? Are there people still left inside?

00:01:00.439 --> 00:01:03.959
I talk with my captain and get my final instructions before I,

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:09.320
before we get there, and then mask up so that I'm ready to go right when we get, when we arrive.

00:01:10.839 --> 00:01:14.680
Over the next four hours, I fulfill various roles fighting the fire,

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:19.639
turning off gas to the house, standing by on the rapid intervention team,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:23.800
and pulling down ceiling, making sure that all the embers and hotspots are completely out.

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:31.400
By the time we get home, it's after midnight. Everyone is safe, the fire is out, and we're all

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:38.680
tired. But like many things in life, there's still one thing left to do, all of the paperwork.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:45.480
The majority of fire departments in the United States are like mine,

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:52.279
volunteer-based organizations. The last estimate put almost 70 percent of fire departments staffed

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:57.400
completely by volunteers. Volunteer fire departments are really, really important

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:01.160
because they protect a section of the country that full-time fire departments just can't.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:06.199
It doesn't make sense to put a full-time fire department in my town of 800 people

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:12.759
like it would in a town of 8,000 people. Because we're volunteers, this is not what we do for a

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:17.559
living. We have day jobs, we have other responsibilities. This is what we do in our

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:23.240
evenings, on weekends, and what little free time we have. But just because we're volunteers doesn't

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:28.839
mean we train any less hard than the full-time firefighters. We're certified to the same standard

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:33.080
and we do a lot of work to make sure that we are certified.

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:42.360
As a volunteer fire department, we often don't have the resources that a full-time fire department has.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:46.039
This becomes especially true when you start to look at data.

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:51.559
As a fire department, there's certain data that we just legally have to have.

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:59.880
Some of that relates to the Federal Emergency Management Agency, or FEMA. After we go on any

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:05.720
type of fire incident, we go to a lovely government form and enter in data very manually,

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:14.039
and then send it off. We provide the data, but it's difficult for us to use. We don't really

00:03:14.039 --> 00:03:21.880
retain a copy that's helpful for us. There are other categories of data. There's patient data,

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:28.759
there's training data, there's all of this data. And it just really wasn't in a spot that we could

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:34.600
leverage it to the best of our abilities. So where did we start? When I joined the

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:40.679
Carin Fire Department a little over a year ago, I walked into my very first Tuesday night drill.

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:45.880
We drill for two hours a week in the evenings to practice anything from how to manage a cardiac

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:51.559
arrest, to how to extricate a patient from a vehicle, or how to run some of the pumps on our

00:03:51.559 --> 00:03:58.279
brush trucks. When I showed up, there was a piece of paper on a clipboard and I wrote my name down.

00:03:58.279 --> 00:04:03.000
This is how we used to track attendance. Now if we were really, really lucky, somebody would

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.520
remember to write down the date of that training and what we were training that night. That paper

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.919
would then get stuck in a filing cabinet that might or might not have looked like this, or it

00:04:12.919 --> 00:04:17.320
would get shoved in the back office in a stack of papers, or it would end up who knows where.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.519
Additionally, when we'd come back from one of our calls or one of our incidents,

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:27.640
we'd get back to the station and go to a whiteboard that's hung on the wall next to our

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:35.079
ambulance. On this whiteboard, we'd write the date, what we responded to, and who was at the call.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:41.480
This would then hopefully get taken a picture of on someone's phone, it would then get texted to

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:47.720
one of the captains, and all of this data would then get entered very manually into a spreadsheet

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:52.279
that is still actually only on one laptop, and that really makes me nervous.

00:04:53.239 --> 00:04:58.359
This took a lot of time, especially from this one captain that had kind of stood up to be our data

00:04:58.359 --> 00:05:06.760
guy. Again, a lot of time unpaid as a volunteer. Now we didn't just track this data because it was

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:13.160
just so much fun, we tracked it because we needed it. As a volunteer in the state of Utah, in order

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:21.079
to respond to structure fires, wildland fires, and EMS calls and be minimally certified, it takes 64

00:05:21.959 --> 00:05:28.440
hours of continuing education every year. That's a lot of time, and these Tuesday evening drills we

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:35.000
have go a long way to making sure we can meet those requirements. Additionally, as we plan

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.040
for our little community, it's really important to know how many times our services are needed.

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:47.160
A couple years ago, there was an idea to put a couple full-time, or sorry, part-time firefighters

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:52.119
at our station Monday to Friday, 9 to 5, because this is a really tough time for volunteers to

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:57.640
cover, as a lot of us are at work. The city started to ask questions, and they were good

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:04.279
questions. Things like, how many calls have you responded to? What time of the day did it happen,

00:06:04.279 --> 00:06:08.279
and what types of calls were they? Were they calls for EMS? Were they calls for fire?

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:13.480
We didn't really have a great way to answer that question. All of the data was there,

00:06:14.119 --> 00:06:21.880
but it wasn't in a usable format. This was a problem. As data analysts, data scientists,

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:27.239
and whatever data person you might identify as, our job is to solve problems at its root.

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:34.119
I proposed that by decreasing repetitive work, making data entry user-friendly,

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:40.359
and leveraging the data, we could solve this problem. I had to start with a question that

00:06:41.079 --> 00:06:45.959
I actually thought quite a bit about the first few weeks as I began to think on this. How do you get

00:06:45.959 --> 00:06:51.720
firefighters to record data? Firefighters and data scientists, as you might guess, come from

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:57.399
different worlds. You might call a firefighter to put out this fire, and you might call a data

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:06.600
scientist to put out these fires. In order to get firefighters to record data, I knew there

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:12.119
was a couple principles that I would have to apply. First, there had to be the minimum input.

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:17.480
Everybody loves sitting down and spending 15, 20, 30 minutes entering data, right?

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:21.880
Yeah. If this was going to take any amount of time, it wasn't going to work. It had to be

00:07:21.880 --> 00:07:29.239
the minimum input. Secondly, it had to be self-explanatory. If we needed training every

00:07:29.239 --> 00:07:34.679
time something changed in the system, or we needed technical documentation, it just wasn't going to

00:07:34.679 --> 00:07:40.119
get used. And finally, it had to be accessible. This wasn't something that we were going to have

00:07:40.119 --> 00:07:45.480
time to break out laptops on, or we had to be at the station to use the station computer to work.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:52.359
This had to be something really agile. So, in order to solve this problem, to meet these requirements,

00:07:52.359 --> 00:07:58.920
and also with no money, and also with just me to rely on, we turned to Shiny. Shiny was a great

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:04.920
solution for this. And so, I began to build a Shiny app. That Shiny app quickly became three

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:11.079
Shiny apps. And so, now we have a Shiny app that helps us track our attendance on Tuesday nights.

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:18.920
We have one that we record our incidents in, or our calls. And finally, we have a data portal

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:25.320
used by officers and administrators to generate reports, manage rosters, trainings, etc.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:31.000
So, now, if you were to come to Corrine, Utah, at 6 p.m. on a Tuesday, and come to our little fire

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.039
station, you'd walk up the stairs into the classroom, and you'd see QR code taped to the

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:42.840
table. The QR code would take you to a Shiny app, where firefighters scan on their phone,

00:08:44.039 --> 00:08:49.479
select their name from a dropdown, and hit check in. I've given an example of what that app might

00:08:50.359 --> 00:08:56.039
look like with some fake data. And below that, you'll see a status table, so we can make sure

00:08:56.039 --> 00:09:01.799
everyone was successfully checked in, see what time they checked out, as well as whatever else

00:09:01.799 --> 00:09:07.960
we might need in the future. And now, when we return from a call, like this one we did that

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:13.320
were about a month ago, instead of writing on that whiteboard, there's now a QR code on that

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:19.400
whiteboard that takes you to our incident response app. Firefighters enter key details about

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:27.000
what the incident was, what firefighters were on what apparatus, anything with wheels, and finally,

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:34.200
after the incident is submitted, you see a summary, so that we can quickly validate

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:39.719
the incident was entered, and it was entered accurately. We're now done. It's in the database.

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:42.440
We don't have to think about it again, and there's no more manual work.

00:09:44.039 --> 00:09:48.760
Finally, this brings us to the data portal. Now, this is the one I'm most excited about,

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:54.599
and I'm sure you guys are excited about. However, we have spent the last year focusing on gathering

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:58.840
data, because you have to have data in order to analyze it, and so there's a lot of blue skies

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:06.919
ahead on this app. Currently, where it stands, it can give immediate status reports of how many

00:10:06.919 --> 00:10:13.239
training hours a firefighter has. These are my training hours from this year. I no longer have

00:10:13.239 --> 00:10:19.320
to wait until the next time somebody sits down to update the spreadsheet and add them all up.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:26.679
It's right there. I know at any point of the year. Additionally, there's an export that exports all

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:33.320
of our training, what the topic was, a short description, any notes. This is really useful

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:38.599
as we go and submit our hours at the end of the year to our licensing organizations.

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:44.760
And finally, like I mentioned, well, I didn't mention, but I meant to mention, we've started

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:48.200
using this instant response app. This one's actually brand new. We've been using it about

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:53.000
two weeks, and I've been out of town the last two weeks, and I'm happy to report

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.400
that the firefighters are using it, and they're loving it. They've got some feedback, but we'll

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:03.000
get there. Three months from now, we have some important reporting deadlines coming up.

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:10.520
One of those being our annual city budget. As you can imagine, rural communities have some budget

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:15.320
constraints, and so we're excited to be able to start to report more to our city council

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:17.960
about why they should continue to fund a local fire department.

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:25.000
One of the features I'm really excited about is our billing feature. We have to be able to

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.840
have money to put gas in the trucks. As we report our incidents and store them in the database,

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:35.320
we're able to generate invoices and billing documents that we can send to the county and

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:42.359
other agencies in the surrounding area. This is something that historically has been a lot of

00:11:42.359 --> 00:11:47.960
manual work and a lot of time that we're now going to be able to get done with Shiny.

00:11:49.559 --> 00:11:53.479
A year from now, I do have some hopes and dreams, and I'm going to say hopes because I just don't

00:11:53.479 --> 00:11:59.080
know where we're going to go. But if I could pick, I would hope that we are able to better plan for

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:03.880
our community that is growing and that we are going to be able to answer questions about should

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:10.840
we put a part-time firefighter at the station. Every fire department in the United States has

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:18.359
an insurance services office rating or classification. This is a really important number.

00:12:18.359 --> 00:12:22.919
You may not know it, but it's one of the driving factors of how much you pay for your home insurance.

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:30.919
And this is the type of data that the insurance services office uses. When we started tracking

00:12:30.919 --> 00:12:35.479
this data in spreadsheets, our classification improved and we're really excited to see what

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:40.359
happens as we provide them more data that they want to know so that they can better classify

00:12:40.359 --> 00:12:46.520
our fire department. And finally, I hope there are other departments using this application.

00:12:47.479 --> 00:12:53.640
This is an open source solution to rural firefighting. All of the code is on GitHub,

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:57.640
and I've built this in the hopes that there are others out there that can use this.

00:13:00.039 --> 00:13:04.039
Nine months ago, when I sat down with the fire chief and the assistant fire chief

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:09.239
and showed them a very, very minimum viable product that just barely worked,

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:13.960
I got done with my presentation and was amazed by the response I got.

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:17.719
The first was from the fire chief who looked at me and said, Joseph,

00:13:17.719 --> 00:13:21.320
this is great. What do you need from us to get this at our department?

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:29.159
I loved having such a positive and open outlook to this new process I was suggesting.

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:33.880
And as cool as that first response was, I think the second response was even better.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:39.559
The assistant chief looked at me and said, Joseph, this is amazing. But can it do this?

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:43.080
What about this? We've always wondered about this.

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:50.679
Between these two, they have 30 years in the fire service as firefighters. They know what

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:56.760
they need. And I'm starting to be able to provide them tools to make their lives easier.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:03.320
At the end of the day, this app is not valuable because it's a work of technical genius.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:08.039
It's a simple wrapper around an AWS database. There's some fun Python scripts that do some

00:14:08.039 --> 00:14:13.320
things in the background. The reason it's valuable is it's the intersection of two worlds.

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:20.919
The fire service and data science. I'm really lucky to live in a community where

00:14:20.919 --> 00:14:26.039
me, this guy right here, who sits most of his day at a keyboard typing away in R,

00:14:27.719 --> 00:14:33.080
can go and serve my community when I'm not working. And I'm hoping that the work I'm doing now

00:14:33.799 --> 00:14:39.880
helps these guys. It helps them do less repetitive work. It helps them have a good

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:43.799
experience entering data and it gives them the ability to leverage data.

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:53.559
At the end of the day, this gives firefighters data tools at their fingertips without writing

00:14:53.559 --> 00:15:00.840
a single line of R or Python code. So that they can focus on what matters. Saving lives,

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:08.679
protecting the community, and getting home to their families safely and timely. Thank you.

00:15:18.119 --> 00:15:23.159
Thank you so much. We do have time for a few questions as well. The first one is,

00:15:23.159 --> 00:15:26.679
where are you posting your Shiny apps? Is your fire department providing support for

00:15:27.239 --> 00:15:32.039
data collection, storage, and usage? Yeah, great question. Right now we're

00:15:32.039 --> 00:15:38.200
on shinyapps.io. After seeing some of the amazing stuff at conference, I think eventually we'll

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:43.960
probably move over to PositConnect Cloud. I've been messing around with that in the evening,

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:51.000
because I'm so excited. As far as data storage, for now I'm still meeting the requirements for

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:56.359
the AWS free tier. And just any incidental fees I'm just covering out of my own pocket,

00:15:56.359 --> 00:15:58.440
because this has been a really fun passion project for me.

00:16:00.359 --> 00:16:04.280
And because you're using your own data collection and manually collected data,

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:09.239
is there a way to compare your volunteer fire department to others in the areas as a benchmark

00:16:09.239 --> 00:16:17.479
of good versus bad on trainings and other metrics? Yeah, I hope so. I think that goes into

00:16:17.479 --> 00:16:22.840
where I hope we're going, that a couple of years from now, we might be able to start publishing

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:27.960
anonymized data saying, hey, look, here are volunteer fire departments from across the

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:33.479
country. Where do you land in terms of what you're doing? And then I guess kind of in addition to that

00:16:33.479 --> 00:16:37.880
with talking about metrics, because it is a volunteer fire department and no one's at the

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:43.080
firehouse at all times, do you track response times, like when a fire is reported versus when

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:48.679
you get there and how that maybe compares to other in the area as well? Yeah, that's one of

00:16:48.679 --> 00:16:54.760
actually the most important metrics, which is probably no surprise. And so we actually do have

00:16:54.760 --> 00:17:01.719
some systems in place. We use a computer aided dispatch system. And so the county tracks that

00:17:01.719 --> 00:17:08.599
for us. So as we arrive and we respond, they record those times for us. And so that's been

00:17:08.599 --> 00:17:14.199
an awesome thing. That is something that we've had in the past, but we were kind of missing some

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:19.719
other parts that were important to us. Okay. And is there any idea of collaboration to collect or

00:17:19.719 --> 00:17:26.359
cross-reference with the 911 call data? Do you have access to that? Yes, we've looked into that.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:34.839
I'm going to punt that question and say, we don't know yet. I know it's out there.

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:40.520
We've looked at doing some API work to maybe see if we could start to bring those together.

00:17:41.479 --> 00:17:44.520
That's actually something we'll probably end up doing at the end of this year as we do our

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:49.959
reporting so we can cross-reference and make sure that it all ties out. And then a question about

00:17:49.959 --> 00:17:54.280
your app. Since creating it, what are some app improvements you're already thinking of?

00:17:55.239 --> 00:18:02.040
A lot of it has been UI focused stuff. A lot of back buttons and refreshes.

00:18:03.560 --> 00:18:09.719
The incident response app, I got a text from one of the firefighters. He said, hey, is there any

00:18:09.719 --> 00:18:13.880
way to do a back button? Because if I mess up, I have to cancel and go through all of it again.

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:19.880
And I was like, oh man, that's not going to be fun. So a lot of it's UI based stuff. And a lot

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:25.959
of it's actually trying to figure out how to track time and date in R in a fun way.

00:18:27.079 --> 00:18:31.800
If you've done stuff with LuberDate, there's a billion things that are fun to play with. So

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:35.479
trying to do that in a sustainable way is something that I'm really focused on.

00:18:35.479 --> 00:18:38.599
And I don't know if you saw the Shiny talk yesterday. There was someone talking about

00:18:38.599 --> 00:18:41.479
the back button for ShinyApp. So you could check it out.

00:18:41.479 --> 00:18:44.040
Oh, sweet. I missed that one. I'm going to have to go watch that one tonight.

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:48.119
She had dynamic URLs and she's like, on a website, you can just click back. And she

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:49.959
added that to her Shiny app. So it's definitely possible.

00:18:49.959 --> 00:18:52.680
Oh, man. I'm really excited. That's awesome.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:55.800
And that's all the questions that we have for right now. So

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:04.680
big shout out to him. Round of applause. And I'll introduce our next speaker.

